The Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) Model is a conceptual framework used to understand how data travels across a network. It divides network communication into seven layers, each with a specific function.
The model helps network engineers and security professionals troubleshoot and understand network traffic.

The 7 Layers:

Layer 7 – Application
Provides network services directly to applications and users.
Examples:

HTTP
HTTPS
DNS
SMTP

Layer 6 – Presentation
Responsible for data formatting, compression, and encryption.

Layer 5 – Session
Establishes, maintains, and terminates communication sessions between devices.

Layer 4 – Transport
Provides end-to-end communication between hosts.

Common protocols:
TCP (reliable)
UDP (faster, less reliable)

Layer 3 – Network
Responsible for routing packets between networks.

Uses:
IP addresses
Routers

Layer 2 – Data Link
Handles communication between devices on the same local network.

Uses:
MAC addresses
Frames

Layer 1 – Physical
Transmits raw bits through physical media.

Examples:

Ethernet cables
Fiber optic cables
Wireless signals
Why the OSI Model Matters

The OSI Model provides a structured way to understand how networks operate and where problems may occur.

For example:

DNS issues occur at Layer 7
IP addressing occurs at Layer 3
Network cables operate at Layer 1

Understanding the OSI Model is fundamental for networking and cybersecurity.

